node.title: MOOSE Conda Packages Now Compatible with Xcode > 12.4
node.bodyText:
Conda package updates for moose-mpich, moose-petsc, and moose-libmesh were merged today in #19230, and enable full MacOS Big Sur compatibility for previously unsupported Xcode and Command Line Tools versions 12.5, 13, and 13.1. This update also enables support for MacOS Monterey. The Clang compiler has also been updated to 12.0.1.
Note that this update only applies to Intel Macs. Official M1 Apple Silicon support is on the way! Track the MOOSE issue #18954 if interested in new developments.
To download the new packages, please activate your MOOSE conda environment and perform the following command:
conda update --all

where the appropriate versions and build in the update output should be:
Package                  Version            Build
=====================================================
moose-libmesh            2021.10.27         build_1
moose-mpich              3.3.2              build_8
moose-petsc              3.15.1             build_3

NOTE that if you do not see build_1 with your libmesh package update, check your python version. If you are using 3.8 or 3.9, you will need to update instead by doing the following:
conda install moose-libmesh moose-tools python=3.7

due to a current lack of PyQt availability in conda for Python 3.8 and 3.9.
If any issues with the new packages are experienced, please open a new Discussions post!

The memory and runtime are "nested" within the main app - so the difference you're seeing there is because of the sub-app.  As a way to think about it - the main app creates the sub-app within it.
The executing timer is timing just the execute() method of the App object.  The App object timer includes everything (setup, etc.).  The memory is always a memory increment.  Therefore the memory that was actually created within execute() and still around when execute() finishes is only 7MB... but the whole app object is holding 37MB.
The PerfGraph for each app is its own... except that the memory and execution time of sub-apps is included within the parent app (as seen here) at a "high" level.  The details of that execution time and memory you can get from the sub-app's PerfGraph.

node.title: Auxvariable vs non-linear variable for chemical potential-driven diffusion coupling
node.bodyText:
Hello,
I'm looking to implement a chemical potential-driven diffusion model, with the following governing equations:
(1)    dC/dt = ( (DC) / (RT) ) * d^2mu / dx^2
(2)    mu = mu_0 + RTln ( C / C_max )
My understanding is that for equation (1) we can use an ADTimeDerivative with variable C, and an ADMatDiffusion with variable = mu coupled to v = C.  An ADParsedMaterial block calculates the coefficient.
I'm not completely clear whether variables linked to kernels must in all cases be non-linear, rather than auxiliary?  It seems that a 'nice' way of setting this problem up would be to set mu as an auxvariable function, which is calculated on every timestep by equation (2) in a ParsedAux block.  Alternatively, mu could be assigned as a non-linear variable and equation (2) evaluated as a material property and mu calculated through a ADMatCoupledForce block.  This seems more difficult.
Which is the best way of doing this, and is it the case that auxvariables can never be linked to kernel calculations?  Thanks.

Hello
Well it really depends what you want your numerical / time integration scheme to be.
If you want to be implicit in C and mu, then use an implicit time scheme and make both non-linear variables.
If you want to be implicit in C and explicit in mu, then use an implicit time scheme and make C a non-linear variable. Then you can choose whether mu should be computed at the beginning or the end of a time step (matters especially for first time step), based on the execute_on of the auxkernel that computes it.
By the way, ADMatDiffusion doesnt do what you think here, because setting the variable to mu does compute the right term, but it places it in the wrong equation.
You have to think of the variable parameter as two things:

it's what goes in the formula for computing that term.
it's the name of equation (equation for C, equation for mu) that you add that term to (that term is part of the residual)

So for that kernel:
v = mu
variable = C
is more correct. You will still need to capture the C-dependency in the diffusivity material property.
Guillaume

Thank you for the advice and the pointer on setting variables to the correct identifier inside kernels - this has cleared up some confusion!  I've gone with the implicit C/explicit mu approach.  I'm finding that the use of a natural log expression in a ParsedAux block is causing an invalid function error.  The same error does not occur when I replace the natural log with a base 10 log (a sanity check to see if other mathematical functions could be used here).  Could you advise on whether the natural log function is supported in the ParsedAux auxkernel?  Many thanks again for the help with this.

According to the documentation for the parser, it should be supported.
Are you writing it ln() or log()? Should be the latter
http://warp.povusers.org/FunctionParser/fparser.html
Ah, that's the issue.  I was using the former.  Thanks for the link to the documentation.

node.title: DiffusionFluxAux & Functor Material Properties
node.bodyText:
Hi:
I am using the NS module with the FV formulation and WCNSFV to run cases with natural convection in a cavity (code converges great!).  For the fluid properties, I am using the Nitrogen fp and making them available using GeneralFunctorFluidProps.
I want to have a VPP for the distribution of the heat flux on the sides of the cavity.  So, I tried using DiffusionFluxAux.  However, this reports the diffusivity 'k' as not existing.  I assume this is because NS::k is a functor and not a traditional material property.  Is that correct?  Do we need new versions of objects such as DiffusionFluxAux that can accept functors?
I tried generating a parallel set of nitrogen properties as normal materials using GeneralFluidProps (adding a suffix to distinguish them).  This didn't work because one of the properties wasn't defined (e_from_something).  Is there anyway to get just the one property that I need?
Note, this is for a user that is simply running a Moose-based app, not someone that wants to modify and rebuild the code.
Thanks,
Joe

Hi Joe
you are right that the issue is with k not being a functor.
i had to do something similar for @muelcm and the way we got to the diffusion flux was through the GenericFunctorGradientAux (or something similar as a functor matprop), with the diffusivity just being the ‘factor’.
I m out today but I ll post a snippet when I come back.
Guillaume

Ok so the workflow I came up with:

use first a GenericFunctorGradientMaterial to get the gradient of the temperature field in a vector function property
use then a ADFunctorElementalVectorAux on each component with the gradient of the temperature as the functor and the diffusivity as the factor. This will populate the auxvariables with each component of the diffusive flux. This will not handle anisotropic diffusion coefficients. Please let me know if you need that.
use the vectorMagnitudeAux to compute the magnitude of the flux.

This gives an "elemental" flux, computed at the centroid of the elements, similarly to the DiffusionFluxAux. It's not exactly the 'true' finite volume flux, which is really computed on the faces of the elements. As we introduce more functionality for face variables into MOOSE, we'll be able to output that, in a face variable. There should be some progress on this by the end of this FY.
Please let me know if that does not work for you

node.title: Setting up automated tests for optional third party library
node.bodyText:
I have created an optional dependency on a third party library (TPL) in the MOOSE app I am working with.  The way in which I did this is:

Compile the TPL separate from my MOOSE app but using the same env as was used for MOOSE compilation
Modify the MOOSE app Makefile to add the TPL lib/include dirs to the ADDITIONAL_INCLUDES and ADDITIONAL_LIBS variables and also define the TPL name in ADDITIONAL_CPPFLAGS.
Create a class in my MOOSE app for interfacing with this TPL.  Ifdef statements are used to only include the TPL calls if the TPL variable was defined in ADDITIONAL_CPPFLAGS.

This allows me to use the TPL successfully as long as it was included in the build.  Now I would like to add some automated tests using the MOOSE testrunner to protect this feature.  However, I need for the test to only be run if the TPL was included during the build and ignored completely otherwise.  Is there a way to do this?

Hello
You need to set up a test group for automated testing. All the tests that will use the TPL will have to be in that group, and when you want to run them you will have to type:
./run_tests -g group_name_with_tpl

Add in the tests file for each concerned test:
group = 'group_name_with_tpl' 
Guillaume

I just tested this and this does allow me to specifically run these tests; however, when I simply type:
./run_tests
the test runner is still picking them up.  This is going to cause these tests to fail if the TPL was not made available during the build.  Is there a way to ensure that group does not get run when the TPL was not made available?

Well you'll have to be running ./run_tests --not_group <group_name>
Or you can hack and mark the tests as heavy. Then they will only be ran with --heavy
Or you can place them in a different folder tests_tpl and only run them with this option:
 -C dir, --test-root dir
                        Tell the TestHarness to search for test spec files at
                        this location.

Thanks, on that last suggestion, isn't the default behavior of the run_tests script to walk the entire directory structure to find any directories that include a tests file?   So even moving these to their own directory will still result in them being picked up.  Unless I'm putting this new subdirectory in the wrong place?

not sure.
It shouldnt pick them up in your_app/
it may pick them up in your_app/test/
I tested moving these tests out of my yourapp/test dir and into the root directory, yourapp, and the runner still finds the tests, so it must just be searching everything from the root down.

Umm. Well I understand you are trying to keep the standard behavior to be ./run_tests and not ./run_tests + some option but I m running out of ideas.
@loganharbour anything I missed to be able to exclude a group of tests by default?
I wouldn't suggest groups here. We should just add the dependency as a test spec option that we can check for. That way, @rks171 can do something like tpl=true in his spec.
@loganharbour, are you saying this would need to be added as a new feature to the test runner?  And would it work by the caller passing in some flag to the run_tests script?
Yes, that's correct

I want to point out that there is another solution for this using submodules.  If the TPL is pulled into the MOOSE app as a git submodule, then any tests that are defined that require that TPL can have the following input added to the test definition:
required_submodule = 'submodule name'

If the submodule is present, the tests will be run, and if not, they will be skipped.

Hi, I have two questions:


If I use a simulation that has not properly ended with a checkpoint or an actual exit as the initial condition for a simulation with a Controls block, do the Controls objects not see the right start_time and end_time?


How would I change my BCs block from


  [./Periodic]
    [./xyz]
      auto_direction = 'x y z'
      variable = 'mag1_x mag1_y mag1_z mag2_x mag2_y mag2_z'
    [../]
  [../]

  [./boundary_grounding2]

    boundary = 'back'
    variable = potential_H_int
    value = 0.0
  [../]

to
  [./Periodic]
    [./xyz]
      auto_direction = 'x y z'
      variable = 'mag1_x mag1_y mag1_z mag2_x mag2_y mag2_z potential_H_int'
    [../]
  [../]

with the TimePeriod controls?
I tried a bit and couldn't get it working so I reverted to two input files and I suspect that the first question here is maybe related to why this didn't seem to work.
thanks!

Hello


The Controls see the simulation time. It does not necessarily match the restart/checkpoint time. When you restart, you specify the timestep that you want to restart from.


This should work, please let us know if it doesnt


[BCs]
  [./Periodic]
    [./xyz]
      auto_direction = 'x y z'
      variable = 'mag1_x mag1_y mag1_z mag2_x mag2_y mag2_z'
    [../]
    [./xyz_later]
      auto_direction = 'x y z'
      variable = 'mag1_x mag1_y mag1_z mag2_x mag2_y mag2_z potential_H_int'
    [../]
  [../]

  [./boundary_grounding1]
    type = FunctionDirichletBC
    boundary = 'front'
    variable = potential_H_int
    function = pulse
  [../]

  [./boundary_grounding2]
    type = DirichletBC
    boundary = 'back'
    variable = potential_H_int
    value = 0.0
  [../]
[]

[Controls]
  [./diff]
    type = TimePeriod
    enable_objects = 'BCs::Periodic::xyz BCs::boundary_grounding1 BCs::boundary_grounding2'
    disable_objects = 'BCs::Periodic::xyz_later'
    start_time = '<simulation_start_time_with_first_set_of_BCs>'

  [../]
[]

When I use that code, I am getting this error from the parser:
*** ERROR ***
The following error occurred in the object "diff", of type "TimePeriod".
The desired parameter 'BCs::Periodic::xyz/enable' was not located for the 'diff' object, it either does not exist or has not been declared as controllable
I ll have a look

I also don't know if immediately making this variable periodic after pulsing the simulation is even the right thing to do :)
thanks!

node.title: Frozen simulation in Performing Initial Setup
node.bodyText:
Dear Community,
I am trying to run a simulation for a mesh with about 12 K nodes and 80-90 K elements. When I run it on a HPC with about 20 cores the simulation get frozen in Performing Initial Setup..... Based on this discussion, I tried less cores but still the same result. When I also try it in my local virtual machine I face the following error:
===
=   BAD TERMINATION OF ONE OF YOUR APPLICATION PROCESSES
=   PID 7259 RUNNING AT alid-VirtualBox
=   EXIT CODE: 9
=   CLEANING UP REMAINING PROCESSES
=   YOU CAN IGNORE THE BELOW CLEANUP MESSAGES


My mesh has three layers. One of them is very thin and when I try to have more nodes in this thin layer the problem pops up. I can have thicker layers with much more nodes and elements and run simulation without any problems but it seems too much nodes in a  thin part of my mesh are source of the problem. I am trying to simulation a TH model using one dirac point. I very much appreciate if anyone can give a hint. My mesh is also uploaded here.
mesh.zip

Hello
So on your local virtual machine, the exit code 9 is most likely because you ran out of memory. To not run out of memory, you can first try to use a distributed mesh --distributed-mesh. Or you can try to use less MPI processes.
On the cluster, we need to find what is actually taking time.
First, can you please try setting more verbose output. I think it's done like this, not sure:
[Outputs]
  [./screen]
    type = Console
    verbose = true
    time_precision = 6
  [../]
[]

Then, are you refining this layer in the MOOSE simulation? How? I dont think the refinement is the problem because there is a console output for that that you would have seen, but it's a commonly slow thing which we can accelerate with certain options.
Finally, is it truly frozen or is there a continuous output of points? Performing Initial Setup.... should gain a new point every like 5 seconds if it's still doing work
Guillaume

Dear @GiudGiud
Firstly, thanks for your time.
I did not get what --distributed-mesh does mean? You mean changing my mesh?
I tried using 6 to 1 cores in my local virtual machine but no result.
I tried also the output option you suggested but nothing changed. About refinement, I did it in the mesh genertaor (GMSH). It is a bit strange because I only have problem when the target layers is thin and lots of nodes are whithin this thin layer. I have created much bigger meshes with more nodes and the same input file works.
About Performing Initial Setup, it is just adding points.

--distributed-mesh is a command line option to get the simulation to distribute the mesh among all processes rather than replicate it. It saves memory.
Your VM could be running out of memory at 1 core already then, which means  --distributed-mesh wont help. If you could make the mesh smaller, by removing some refinement probably, then you could debug the problem on your VM.
To identify what is taking so long, the easiest way is to reduce the mesh and profile the code.
We have instructions here on how to do that: https://mooseframework.inl.gov/application_development/profiling.html

@GiudGiud
Thanks again for your time.
My problem is really getting strange. I tried several meshes and it seems if I make the mesh finer just more than a limit in the res layer (the target layer), the mesh won't work anymore in MOOSE. I have uploade two meshes and if you have a look at them, the difference between Working and NotWorking meshes is very subtle!
mesh.zip
Can you upload exodus files? On a github repo too please. I m not supposed to open zip files from the internet on my workstation

Dear @GiudGiud,
Sorry for my late feedback.
My problem solved just by adding more nodes to the mesh! When the difference between number of nodes in each volume is extreme, it doesnot work. I applied two solutions: reducing number of nodes in target layers or adding nodes to other two layers.
I uploaded files in my repo. You can find it here: https://github.com/Ali1990dashti/Mesh_files. Both meshes are almost the same but Working mesh has less nodes in target volume.

This mesh has lots of issues. I recommend you rework the meshing to make sure the elements arent as skewed, dont have huge aspect ratios and have reasonable gradient in sizes. There's huge elements touching very small ones.
Even if we found why the initialization is freezing, the results you would get from the solve would be bad.
You can either improve the mesh in gmsh or use the free version of cubit https://coreform.com/products/coreform-cubit/free-meshing-software/. That should get you nicer meshes (though limited in size)
Thanks for your hints and time. As you said, the mesh is causing all these issues.

node.title: Steady State Solution Iterated with Trasient Solution.
node.bodyText: Is it possible to solve steady state and transient problems in a singe .i file? The physics for each are different (steady state flow, transient heat transfer) but parameters can be shared from each solution type to the other?

Hello
Yes but it's kind of hacky.
If you 'forget' the time derivatives for some variables, they will be solved for their steady state value.
Numerically, there is no guarantee it will work. But it's been done before for flow and heat conduction.
Guillaume
I expect that I could put the solvers in sequential order, i.e. steady state first, then transient to gain the sequential solutions? Are there any example problems for this? Thank you.

no they will be solved simultaneously.
If you want to order solves you ll have to use the Multiapps system, which wont use the same .i file.
That is the cannon way of doing this.
